AB  - The primary objective for implementing continuous processing is cost reduction of operations in the production of biopharmaceuticals, motivated by high production costs and the promise of significant productivity gains from continuous operations. However, changing the currently prevailing production technology from batch operation to continuous operation will have broad implications on manufacturing and quality systems. The realization of integrated continuous operations in large scale biopharmaceutical manufacturing needs to take existing constraints into account. Regulatory expectation and quality procedures and their impact on the design of operations have to be respected. Operational challenges like supply flexibility, process scale turndown, equipment complexity, fault recovery, and aseptic sampling have to be addressed. Utilization of "single use" equipment, equipment utilization, and the application of process analytical technologies have impact of process and facility design. © 2018 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
